note.body: Hi, I can confirm that this dummy display works

target_title: NdCCSink: Error received: Media load failed

note.body:
h264 is a very universal codec so that should definitely be supported, maybe `vah264enc` is causing the issue. @loutr Would you mind running the app with these env vars, for flatpak it would be:
```
NETWORK_DISPLAYS_DUMMY=1 G_MESSAGES_DEBUG=all flatpak run org.gnome.NetworkDisplays
```

and then see if the stream works locally. In the logs there should be a line like this:
```
Gnd-Message: 13:12:30.443: NdDummyCCSink: You should now be able to connect to http://localhost:39889/
```

Connect to the stream using the same url and see if the stream is visible.
```
mpv http://localhost:39889/
```

Are you running this under X11 or Wayland?

target_title: Samsung TV not found

note.body:
GND only discovers devices via mDNS, it's possible the device doesn't advertise there.
Closing as there is nothing we can do here unfortunately. If there's new insights, please post them here and I'll reopen.

target_title: Remove audio sink after disconnection

note.body:
I was just about to report this exact issue. Luckily I found this existing bug report and spared you from a duplicate :-).

I don't think the application crashing should be a concern here. I use this awesome application very often and it has never crashed on me. Either way, even if that does happen, that would be a different issue and a lingering sink would not be such a big issue in that case...

I think you should add a proper cleanup for the case when it does not crash. This would be amazing.

- Right now when I cast to my TV I have to use the settings to switch audio to the "Network Displays" virtual sink.
- When I exit Network Displays the audio remains on the lingering virtual sink which is annoying. I have to manually switch back to speakers/headphones
- If instead I use a utility such as "coppwr" to destroy the lingering sink, the audio reverts back to my previously active device automatically!
- Adding the cleanup when exiting, would also automatically revert the audio back to the original device, which would be very user friendly

I would definitely recommend you add a simple cleanup when you stop streaming (or at least when you exit the application).

note.body:
You are missing a video encoder...x264enc should work, but you probably want hardware encoding instead.
In Fedora 41+ `vaapih264enc` has been superseded and replaced by `vah264enc`.

If you have an Intel machine that's in the `intel-media-driver` RPM. You can check for it via:
```
gst-inspect-1.0 vah264enc
``` 
The high latency is a known issue with our Chromecast implementation.

note.body:
I also tried different settings for the other issues, changing renderer/encoder with --env=GSK_RENDERER=gl --env=NETWORK_DISPLAYS_H264_ENC=openh264enc /x264 but with no differences. Using GSK_RENDERER removes the vulcan issues but doesn't work anyway.

I also tried to directly access to the local port send the stream, I got a reader but no sound/video where displayed so I guess it's more a local issue that remote chromecast one ?

If you some ideas or thinks I could try, thanks.

target_title: No video using Xiamo Mi Stick
Core dumped after a few minutes

note.body:
Hi,
Sorry for the delay i tried again with 2 differents computers running 0.94.0, No more coredump, but unfortunatly video doesn't work (detected but black screen on the receiver), audio kind of works but lagging a lot. I will create a new report with detailled info.
Thanks.

target_title: Core dumped after a few minutes
WFDP2P: wpa_supplicant connection fails

target_title: [solved] not able to connect to LGwebOS under fedora41 (Gnome47)

note.body:
Right, you have it; in that case you probably have a different problem.

Maybe your Wi-Fi card driver just does not have proper support for Wi-Fi Direct (also known as P2P) on Linux? You can check using `iw phy | grep -A 10 "valid interface combinations"`, it should list "P2P-device" there and show that you can use it in parallel with a managed interface.

note.body:
dnsmasq is needed by NetworkManager and is part of the core operating system in this case. It has to be available on the system, otherwise the Wi-Fi P2P connection does not fully work.

You can still use the Flatpak gnome-network-displays. Just install dnsmasq on the system and use the Flatpak afterwards.

target_title: Connecting Fedora PC to Samsung TV using MICE

note.body:
MICE discovery works via DNS-SD. Your router might not propagate mDNS from wifi to wired.
Under the hood, GND essentially does `avahi-browse _display._tcp -rt` for discovery. What does that yield for you?
If there's no output, then GND won't be able to discover anything either.
You could then try to connect both (TV and PC) via wifi or via ethernet to your router to see if mDNS properly propagates that way.

Also try `avahi-browse -art` to see what other mDNS entries can be discovered.

target_title: Make resolution manually configurable
Casting from Ubuntu to LG 4k TV --- "WfdClient: No resolution found, falling back to standard FullHD."

note.body:
There's a couple of things here, none of them are going to be very helpful to you though:
- Casting photos as video screencast generally isn't efficient and often not too effective either (bad quality) which will result in a bad experience. Some protocols like ChromeCast and AirPlay have dedicated modes for displaying still pictures/photos but those aren't currently implemented here (and would require quite a lot of work). Not sure whether there's a Wayland protocol for that yet that apps could implement on the Linux side.
- The resolution selection code (for selection depending on what the TV advertises) is currently disabled in GND because many TVs advertise nonsense (see also https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-network-displays/-/issues/154). I think this has since improved and we should re-evaluate re-enabling it.
- LG 4k TVs do not advertise 4k support via Miracast/Chromecast (at least the 2 models I own did not last I checked). Technically, casting a 4k video to my 2020 model via Miracast does work really well, but the newer 2023 model has big trouble with it and shows large decoding artifacts.
- We may want to make this configurable with a manual override.

What was the problem with GNOME Settings? With one adapter, it can be easily disabled. If that's not the case with two (or more) adapters, that should be a Settings issue: https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-control-center/-/issues

Having multiple wifi adapters on one system is rather an edge case. Also, with avahi for DNS-SD discovery (used for MICE and ChromeCast), it's unfortunately not possible to specify the interface to search on.
